{"key":"processedPost-6828180","value":{"id":6828180,"first":6828146,"last":18653973,"when":1177452970,"utime":"04/25/07 01:16 AM","content":"Don't get your growing information from erowid.  Do a search here under my name for terrariums.   Perlite will supply the humidity, and drilling a hundred or more holes will provide air exchange.  You don't need or want mechanical devices such as humidifiers on a small terrarium.<br /><br />The picture below is how I build terrariums by drilling holes into all six sides and then filling with three to five inches of rinsed, then well drained perlite.<br />RR<br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-14/575087590-Shiitake_on_pf_tek8a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-14/575087590-thumb_Shiitake_on_pf_tek8a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-009/287245516-Terrarium_2a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-009/287245516-thumb_Terrarium_2a.jpg\"></a>","title":"Re: CO2 in terrarium","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}